{
  "text": "Head and neck cancer (HNC) survivors often have to deal with devastating consequences of this type of cancer and its treatment, such as pain, fatigue, problems with speech and swallowing, and changes in facial appearance. These effects negatively affect their health-related quality of life [CITATION_1] , and over 25% of HNC survivors suffer from clinical levels of distress [CITATION_2] . However, in this population, moderate to high levels of PTG have consistently been found [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , which are comparable to levels of PTG in other cancer populations [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . In a systematic review including five studies, Harding and colleagues identified several factors that seem to be associated with PTG in HNC survivors: younger age at diagnosis, relationship status, positive reframing, optimism, and hope [CITATION_9] .",
  "correct_citation": {
